EXPANSIONS = {'node-streams-backpressure': {'body': 'pipe with highWaterMark and pause/resume prevents memory blowup on slow consumers.\n\n## Problem in production\n\npipe with highWaterMark and pause/resume prevents memory blowup on slow consumers.\n\nTeams shipping node streams backpressure without failure-mode rehearsal discover gaps during peak traffic, not in sprint review.\n\n## Core design\n\nSeparate policy from enforcement for node streams backpressure. Document invariants, log evidence, test rollback paths.\n\n## Implementation\n\nStart smallest: one service, one environment, measurable SLI for node streams backpressure.\n\n## Code patterns\n\nReference patterns below match production conventions.\n\n```typescript\n// node-streams-backpressure — illustrative production skeleton\nexport async function handler(input: unknown) {\n  const validated = schema.parse(input);\n  const result = await withTimeout(doWork(validated), 5000);\n  return { ok: true, result };\n}\n```\n\n## Failure modes\n\nMissing idempotency, implicit defaults differing across environments, and dashboards green while users fail—classic node streams backpressure incidents.\n\n## Observability\n\nMetrics: latency histogram, error rate, saturation. Logs: structured JSON with trace_id. Traces: one span per dependency.\n\n## Security\n\nLeast privilege credentials, no secrets in logs, fail closed on auth paths.\n\n## Rollout checklist\n\nFeature flag, canary, rollback tested, load test at 2x peak before marketing launch.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://nodejs.org/docs](https://nodejs.org/docs)\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': []}, 'oauth-pkce-mobile': {'body': 'Client secret in APK failed security review. PKCE replaces secret with per-login verifier.\n\n## Verifier generation\n\n32 random bytes, SHA256 challenge, S256 method only.\n\n## Authorization request\n\nInclude code_challenge and state for CSRF protection.\n\n## Token exchange\n\nSend code_verifier—intercepted code useless without it.\n\n## Secure storage\n\niOS Keychain, Android Keystore—never plain SharedPreferences.\n\n## Universal Links\n\nPrefer over custom URL schemes to reduce interception.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': []}, 'nextjs-middleware-edge-runtime': {'body': 'Middleware runs on Edge for geo routing, auth gates, and header rewrites before render.\n\n## Problem in production\n\nMiddleware runs on Edge for geo routing, auth gates, and header rewrites before render.\n\nTeams shipping nextjs middleware edge runtime without failure-mode rehearsal discover gaps during peak traffic, not in sprint review.\n\n## Core design\n\nSeparate policy from enforcement for nextjs middleware edge runtime. Document invariants, log evidence, test rollback paths.\n\n## Implementation\n\nStart smallest: one service, one environment, measurable SLI for nextjs middleware edge runtime.\n\n## Code patterns\n\nReference patterns below match production conventions.\n\n```typescript\n// nextjs-middleware-edge-runtime — illustrative production skeleton\nexport async function handler(input: unknown) {\n  const validated = schema.parse(input);\n  const result = await withTimeout(doWork(validated), 5000);\n  return { ok: true, result };\n}\n```\n\n## Failure modes\n\nMissing idempotency, implicit defaults differing across environments, and dashboards green while users fail—classic nextjs middleware edge runtime incidents.\n\n## Observability\n\nMetrics: latency histogram, error rate, saturation. Logs: structured JSON with trace_id. Traces: one span per dependency.\n\n## Security\n\nLeast privilege credentials, no secrets in logs, fail closed on auth paths.\n\n## Rollout checklist\n\nFeature flag, canary, rollback tested, load test at 2x peak before marketing launch.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://nextjs.org/docs](https://nextjs.org/docs)\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': []}, 'nextjs-image-optimization': {'body': 'LCP at 4.2 seconds from a 3.2MB PNG on mobile. next/image generates srcsets, serves AVIF/WebP, reserves layout space, and lazy-loads below-fold content.\n\n## Basic usage\n\nStatic imports provide width, height, blurDataURL at build time.\n\n```tsx\n<Image src={hero} alt="Hero" priority placeholder="blur" sizes="100vw" />\n```\n\n## The sizes attribute\n\nMatch sizes to CSS layout—not source dimensions. Wrong sizes wastes bandwidth or serves blurry images.\n\n## Remote images\n\nConfigure remotePatterns allowlist—never wildcard hostname in production.\n\n```javascript\nremotePatterns: [{ protocol: "https", hostname: "cdn.example.com" }],\n```\n\n## Priority and LCP\n\nOne priority image per page—typically hero. Adds preload, disables lazy load.\n\n## Fill layout\n\nParent needs position relative and aspect ratio for fill prop.\n\n## Custom CDN loader\n\nAt scale, delegate to Cloudinary/Imgix via custom loaderFile.\n\n## Production checklist\n\nCap deviceSizes, quality 75 for photos, monitor Image Optimization API usage.\n\n## Failure modes\n\nMissing priority on LCP, wrong sizes, permissive remotePatterns open proxy risk.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://nextjs.org/docs](https://nextjs.org/docs)\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': [('next/image vs img?', 'Use next/image when dimensions known—automatic srcset, format negotiation, CLS prevention.'), ('External CDN images?', 'Add remotePatterns or custom loader pointing to CDN transforms.'), ('Slow LCP image?', 'Add priority, correct sizes, appropriately sized source file.')]}, 'nextjs-metadata-seo-api': {'body': 'generateMetadata merges layout and page metadata with type-safe Open Graph tags.\n\n## Problem in production\n\ngenerateMetadata merges layout and page metadata with type-safe Open Graph tags.\n\nTeams shipping nextjs metadata seo api without failure-mode rehearsal discover gaps during peak traffic, not in sprint review.\n\n## Core design\n\nSeparate policy from enforcement for nextjs metadata seo api. Document invariants, log evidence, test rollback paths.\n\n## Implementation\n\nStart smallest: one service, one environment, measurable SLI for nextjs metadata seo api.\n\n## Code patterns\n\nReference patterns below match production conventions.\n\n```typescript\n// nextjs-metadata-seo-api — illustrative production skeleton\nexport async function handler(input: unknown) {\n  const validated = schema.parse(input);\n  const result = await withTimeout(doWork(validated), 5000);\n  return { ok: true, result };\n}\n```\n\n## Failure modes\n\nMissing idempotency, implicit defaults differing across environments, and dashboards green while users fail—classic nextjs metadata seo api incidents.\n\n## Observability\n\nMetrics: latency histogram, error rate, saturation. Logs: structured JSON with trace_id. Traces: one span per dependency.\n\n## Security\n\nLeast privilege credentials, no secrets in logs, fail closed on auth paths.\n\n## Rollout checklist\n\nFeature flag, canary, rollback tested, load test at 2x peak before marketing launch.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://nextjs.org/docs](https://nextjs.org/docs)\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': []}, 'oauth2-authorization-code-flow': {'body': 'Authorization code with PKCE—never implicit flow, never localStorage tokens.\n\n## Problem in production\n\nAuthorization code with PKCE—never implicit flow, never localStorage tokens.\n\nTeams shipping oauth2 authorization code flow without failure-mode rehearsal discover gaps during peak traffic, not in sprint review.\n\n## Core design\n\nSeparate policy from enforcement for oauth2 authorization code flow. Document invariants, log evidence, test rollback paths.\n\n## Implementation\n\nStart smallest: one service, one environment, measurable SLI for oauth2 authorization code flow.\n\n## Code patterns\n\nReference patterns below match production conventions.\n\n```typescript\n// oauth2-authorization-code-flow — illustrative production skeleton\nexport async function handler(input: unknown) {\n  const validated = schema.parse(input);\n  const result = await withTimeout(doWork(validated), 5000);\n  return { ok: true, result };\n}\n```\n\n## Failure modes\n\nMissing idempotency, implicit defaults differing across environments, and dashboards green while users fail—classic oauth2 authorization code flow incidents.\n\n## Observability\n\nMetrics: latency histogram, error rate, saturation. Logs: structured JSON with trace_id. Traces: one span per dependency.\n\n## Security\n\nLeast privilege credentials, no secrets in logs, fail closed on auth paths.\n\n## Rollout checklist\n\nFeature flag, canary, rollback tested, load test at 2x peak before marketing launch.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': []}, 'oauth2-client-credentials-m2m': {'body': 'Machine clients exchange client_id/secret for service tokens without user context.\n\n## Problem in production\n\nMachine clients exchange client_id/secret for service tokens without user context.\n\nTeams shipping oauth2 client credentials m2m without failure-mode rehearsal discover gaps during peak traffic, not in sprint review.\n\n## Core design\n\nSeparate policy from enforcement for oauth2 client credentials m2m. Document invariants, log evidence, test rollback paths.\n\n## Implementation\n\nStart smallest: one service, one environment, measurable SLI for oauth2 client credentials m2m.\n\n## Code patterns\n\nReference patterns below match production conventions.\n\n```typescript\n// oauth2-client-credentials-m2m — illustrative production skeleton\nexport async function handler(input: unknown) {\n  const validated = schema.parse(input);\n  const result = await withTimeout(doWork(validated), 5000);\n  return { ok: true, result };\n}\n```\n\n## Failure modes\n\nMissing idempotency, implicit defaults differing across environments, and dashboards green while users fail—classic oauth2 client credentials m2m incidents.\n\n## Observability\n\nMetrics: latency histogram, error rate, saturation. Logs: structured JSON with trace_id. Traces: one span per dependency.\n\n## Security\n\nLeast privilege credentials, no secrets in logs, fail closed on auth paths.\n\n## Rollout checklist\n\nFeature flag, canary, rollback tested, load test at 2x peak before marketing launch.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': []}, 'nextjs-caching-revalidation': {'body': 'A content editor published a pricing change at 9:02 AM. Support tickets started at 9:15—not because the database was wrong, but because the marketing homepage still showed last week\'s numbers. Three separate cache layers, one incident. Next.js App Router caching is a stack, not a switch.\n\n## The four cache layers\n\nRequest memoization deduplicates identical fetch calls within one server render. The Data Cache stores HTTP responses. The Full Route Cache stores prerendered HTML. The Router Cache stores RSC payloads on the client.\n\nDebugging stale data requires identifying which layer serves the response—hard refresh vs client navigation symptoms differ.\n\n## Fetch cache options\n\nUse next.revalidate for TTL, tags for on-demand invalidation, cache no-store for user-specific data.\n\n```typescript\nconst post = await fetch(`${API}/posts/${slug}`, {\n  next: { tags: [`post-${slug}`], revalidate: 60 },\n});\n```\n\n## On-demand revalidation\n\nCall revalidateTag after CMS webhooks and revalidatePath for URL-scoped invalidation. Protect webhook endpoints with secrets.\n\n```typescript\nexport async function publishPost(slug: string) {\n  await db.post.update({ where: { slug }, data: { published: true } });\n  revalidateTag(`post-${slug}`);\n  revalidatePath("/blog");\n}\n```\n\n## Route segment config\n\ndynamic force-dynamic opts out of static cache. revalidate on segment sets ISR interval. cookies() in layout forces dynamic subtree.\n\n## unstable_cache for databases\n\nDirect ORM queries bypass fetch cache—wrap with unstable_cache and tags matching your domain events.\n\n## Security and over-caching\n\nNever statically cache authenticated routes. Two users seeing the same cached /account response is a vulnerability.\n\n## Multi-instance self-hosted\n\nrevalidateTag on one pod does not invalidate others without shared cache—plan Redis or CDN purge coordination.\n\n## Testing cache behavior\n\nUse next build && next start. Integration tests call revalidate API and assert UI freshness.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://nextjs.org/docs](https://nextjs.org/docs)\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': [('Why stale data after DB update?', 'Database updates do not invalidate Next.js caches. Call revalidatePath or revalidateTag, or use cache no-store.'), ('revalidatePath vs revalidateTag?', 'Path invalidates URL cache. Tags invalidate all fetches tagged—better when one API feeds many pages.'), ('Does next dev reflect production caching?', 'No—always validate with production build.')]}, 'node-worker-threads-cpu': {'body': 'worker_threads for bcrypt, image resize—never block event loop on CPU work.\n\n## Problem in production\n\nworker_threads for bcrypt, image resize—never block event loop on CPU work.\n\nTeams shipping node worker threads cpu without failure-mode rehearsal discover gaps during peak traffic, not in sprint review.\n\n## Core design\n\nSeparate policy from enforcement for node worker threads cpu. Document invariants, log evidence, test rollback paths.\n\n## Implementation\n\nStart smallest: one service, one environment, measurable SLI for node worker threads cpu.\n\n## Code patterns\n\nReference patterns below match production conventions.\n\n```typescript\n// node-worker-threads-cpu — illustrative production skeleton\nexport async function handler(input: unknown) {\n  const validated = schema.parse(input);\n  const result = await withTimeout(doWork(validated), 5000);\n  return { ok: true, result };\n}\n```\n\n## Failure modes\n\nMissing idempotency, implicit defaults differing across environments, and dashboards green while users fail—classic node worker threads cpu incidents.\n\n## Observability\n\nMetrics: latency histogram, error rate, saturation. Logs: structured JSON with trace_id. Traces: one span per dependency.\n\n## Security\n\nLeast privilege credentials, no secrets in logs, fail closed on auth paths.\n\n## Rollout checklist\n\nFeature flag, canary, rollback tested, load test at 2x peak before marketing launch.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://nodejs.org/docs](https://nodejs.org/docs)\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': []}, 'oauth2-device-flow-tv': {'body': 'TV has no keyboard for OAuth redirect. Device flow splits auth across TV display and phone browser.\n\n## Flow sequence\n\nDevice gets user_code, user authorizes on phone, TV polls token endpoint.\n\n## Polling\n\nRespect interval and slow_down. Exponential backoff with jitter.\n\n## TV UX\n\nLarge monospace code, countdown timer, QR for verification_uri_complete.\n\n## Refresh tokens\n\nLong-lived for TVs—store in secure hardware, revoke server-side on logout.\n\n## Security\n\nRate limit device authorization, exclude ambiguous characters from user codes.\n\n## Resources\n\n- [https://oauth.net/2/](https://oauth.net/2/)', 'faq': []}}

FAQ_OVERRIDES = {'nextjs-csp-headers-middleware': [('CSP without dynamic pages?', 'Nonce CSP prevents HTML CDN caching—split static marketing from dynamic app.'), ('Why hydration breaks?', 'Missing nonce on bootstrap script—check console violated-directive.'), ('style-src unsafe-inline?', 'Often required for CSS-in-JS—do not weaken script-src to compensate.')]}
